06484nam a22010695i 9780231540735DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20162015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015014532  a(OCoLC)979577734  a97802315407357 a10.7312/cohe168702doi  a(DE-B1597)468900  a(OCoLC)933388574  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBL640b.R34 2016 7aREL0840002bisacsh  aBE 9020qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/10825:00aReligion, Secularism, and Constitutional Democracy /ced. by Cécile Laborde, Jean Cohen. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2016] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (464 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion, Culture, and Public Life ;v200 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPolarization between political religionists and militant secularists on both sides of the Atlantic is on the rise. Critically engaging with traditional secularism and religious accommodationism, this collection introduces a constitutional secularism that robustly meets contemporary challenges. It identifies which connections between religion and the state are compatible with the liberal, republican, and democratic principles of constitutional democracy and assesses the success of their implementation in the birthplace of political secularism: the United States and Western Europe.Approaching this issue from philosophical, legal, historical, political, and sociological perspectives, the contributors wage a thorough defense of their project's theoretical and institutional legitimacy. Their work brings fresh insight to debates over the balance of human rights and religious freedom, the proper definition of a nonestablishment norm, and the relationship between sovereignty and legal pluralism. They discuss the genealogy of and tensions involving international legal rights to religious freedom, religious symbols in public spaces, religious arguments in public debates, the jurisdiction of religious authorities in personal law, and the dilemmas of religious accommodation in national constitutions and public policy when it violates international human rights agreements or liberal-democratic principles. If we profoundly rethink the concepts of religion and secularism, these thinkers argue, a principled adjudication of competing claims becomes possible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFreedom of religion. 0aGesetzgebung. 0aInternationaler Vergleich. 0aMenschenrecht. 0aPluralistische Gesellschaft. 0aPolitical theology. 0aReligion and politics. 0aReligion and state. 0aReligion. 0aReligionsfreiheit. 0aStaat. 0aSäkularisierung. 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh1 aAccetti, Carlo Invernizzi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBardon, Aurélia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhargava, Rajeev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jean L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Jean, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErgas, Yasmine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimm, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaupt, Claudia E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoppke, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaborde, Cécile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaborde, Cécile, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLacorne, Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalik, Maleiha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v